hands_on_practices.problem:
An electron is confined within a one-dimensional infinite potential well of width $L$. The potential $V(x)$ is $0$ for $0 < x < L$ and infinite otherwise. At time $t=0$, the electron's state is not a stationary state of the well, but is instead described by the normalized wavefunction:
$$
\Psi(x, 0) = \begin{cases} 
      \sqrt{\frac{12}{L^3}} x & 0 \le x \le \frac{L}{2} \\
      \sqrt{\frac{12}{L^3}} (L-x) & \frac{L}{2} < x \le L \\
      0 & \text{otherwise}
   \end{cases}
$$
If the energy of the electron is measured at this instant ($t=0$), what is the probability of finding the electron in the ground state of the well?

Give your answer as a dimensionless number rounded to four significant figures.
